  "prompt": "What are codons and where are they located?",
  "response": "Codons are three-nucleotide sequences in DNA and RNA that serve as the basic units of genetic code. Here are key details about codons:\n\nLocation:\n1. In DNA: Located along the coding strand of genes\n2. In mRNA (messenger RNA): Transcribed from DNA during gene expression\n\nCharacteristics:\n- Consist of 3 consecutive nucleotide bases\n- Specify a particular amino acid or signal start/stop of protein synthesis\n- Read in a specific direction (5' to 3')\n\nTypes of Codons:\n1. Start codon (AUG): Signals the beginning of protein translation\n2. Stop codons (UAA, UAG, UGA): Signal the end of protein translation\n3. Sense codons: Code for specific amino acids\n\nFunction:\n- Translate genetic information from nucleic acids to proteins\n- Determine the sequence of amino acids during protein synthesis\n- Essential for genetic information transfer in living organisms\n\nReading:\n- Codons are read sequentially during translation\n- Each codon corresponds to a specific amino acid\n- The genetic code is nearly universal across different organisms\n\nCodons play a crucial role in gene expression and protein synthesis by serving as the fundamental language of genetic information.",
